      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1d4a4b72ffe5f46a",
      "text": "First Steps / Minimum Viable Product. [https://github.com/matrix-org/thirdroom/discussions discussions]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d7ae79febedee898",
      "text": "* We will be developing a more polished and feature-complete version of the original Third Room demo.\n* Users will be able to sign in to their Matrix account using OpenID Connect\n* They will be able to create Matrix rooms containing 3D virtual worlds by choosing from one of the provided scenes or uploading their own glTF scene. The room's scene will be stored in Matrix. A screenshot/thumbnail of this scene will also be stored in Matrix to show in room listings and when loading the scene. This scene may include a Web Assembly script which will have some scripting capabilities to add interactivity to the room.\n* Users will be able to view a list of their joined rooms, search for public rooms, and invite others to their rooms.\n* They will be able to customize and pick their avatar from an existing set or upload their own using either the Mozilla Hubs avatar skeleton or VRM skeleton, both represented as a glTF avatar. Their profile containing this avatar will be stored in Matrix.\n* Users will be able to use text and voice chat to talk to other users in the room. This will be based on top of Matrix and the Matrix Group Calls work. Connections to other users in the room will be made via P2P WebRTC connections and SFUs will not be in place for the MVP.\n* Users will be able to walk around these virtual worlds, embodying their avatar in both 3rd and 1st person. Avatars with and without legs will be supported. XR support will not be in the MVP.\n* Users will be able to see the list of users in the room and block, kick, or ban other users depending on their permissions in the room.\n* Users will be able to quickly jump between scenes via links inside rooms or by clicking on rooms in the room list.\n* Users will be able to access rooms, avatars, and various assets across multiple thirdroom servers. Federation will be enabled from the start.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ab2f4a256e5fa807",
      "text": "Tech Stack"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "348d0e00006041b6",
      "text": "\n* Synapse: Matrix Homeserver\n* Hydrogen SDK: Lightweight, performance-focused, Matrix Client SDK\n* React: Frontend UI framework\n* Vite: fast/low-configuration JS bundler/dev server\n* Three.js: WebGL 3D rendering library\n* Rapier.js: Rust/WASM physics library with first-class, well-documented JS API\n* bitECS: Fast, data-oriented, JS ECS library\n* three-omi: Support for loading OMI glTF extensions\n* three-vrm: Support for loading VRM avatars\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "690e3fb159851816",
      "text": "[…] the physics engine: currently, objects are ‘owned’ by the account which created them, which then runs the physics simulation for that object and then pushes the results out to the other users in the room to update their world view. We are not yet running a decentralised physics simulation, sadly :) We have plans to improve this in future however. [https://thirdroom.io/preview#what-makes-us-unique page]"
    }
